ictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin); French (<b>Béthune</b>): habitational name from Béthune in Pas-de-Calais, Picardy, France, recorded in the 8th century in the Latin form <i>Bitunia</i>, probably an adjective (with <i>villa</i> understood) derived from the oblique form of an ancient Germanic personal name <i>Betto</i>, an assimilated form of <i>Berto</i> (see   Bert  ). See also Scottish   Beaton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beaton","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Béthune in Pas-de-Calais, France (see   Bethune  ). The Hebridean family of   McBeth  , hereditary physicians, adopted the surname <i>Beaton</i> in the 16th century.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Beton</i>, a diminutive of <i>Bete</i>, a pet form of <i>Beatrice</i> (see   Beatrice  ). Compare   Beat  .","English: variant of   Betton  ."]},{"name":"Bert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philibert, Pierre.","German, French, and Polish: from a short form of various compound personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ (see for example   Bertram  ).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Berte</i> (Old French <i>Berte</i>, from ancient Germanic   Berta  )."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume V de Béthune was born in 1270, in France as the son of Guillaume IV deBethune and Jeanne de Nesle Falvy. He married Marie DE ROYE de la FERTÉ in 1315. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 13 April 1340, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1270–13Apr1340":"1270–13. aprill 1340","1270–1340":"1270–1340","1272–1339":"1272–1339","1280–1324":"1280–1324","–1340":"–1340","1277–1349":"1277–1349","1317–1362":"1317–1362","–1384":"–1384","1236–1279":"1236–1279","–1280":"–1280","circa 1280":"umbes 1280","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","1324":"1324","1279":"1279","1277":"1277","13Apr1340":"13. aprill 1340","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Locres, France":"Prantsusmaa","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Lokeren, Flandre Orientale, Belgium":"Lokeren, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"1270–13Apr1340":"1270–13. huhtikuuta 1340","1270–1340":"1270–1340","1272–1339":"1272–1339","1280–1324":"1280–1324","–1340":"–1340","1277–1349":"1277–1349","1317–1362":"1317–1362","–1384":"–1384","1236–1279":"1236–1279","–1280":"–1280","circa 1280":"noin 1280","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","1324":"1324","1279":"1279","1277":"1277","13Apr1340":"13. huhtikuuta 1340","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Locres, France":"Ranska","Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk":"Béthune, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska","Lokeren, Flandre Orientale, Belgium":"Lokeren, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fr":{"1270–13Apr1340":"1270–13 avril 1340","1270–1340":"1270–1340","1272–1339":"1272–1339","1280–1324":"1280–1324","–1340":"–1340","1277–13